Project Title: Cory Covid-Bot User Acceptance Testing

You are invited to take part in this study. Please read this Explanatory Statement in full before deciding whether or not to participate in this research. If you would like further information regarding any aspect of this project, you are encouraged to contact the researchers via the email addresses listed above.
What is the purpose of this research project?

This project is meant to improve our understanding of how people will interact with a chatbot that is aimed at informing people about the disease COVID-19 and what they can do to make the best choices in light of the newest information available. In addition, we are interested in knowing which resources individuals are most likely to request from the chatbot, so we can improve the usefulness of the technology and optimize the user experience.

This project aims to identify the strengths and weaknesses of this technological aid in helping people understand the virus and its effects, as well as the current and future guidelines from the government. This will aid in improving people's knowledge on key factors of viral transmission and in making more informed decisions in their daily lives.
Why were you chosen for this research?
This study is looking for healthy adults. To be included, you must meet the following criteria:

column2: You don't have any trouble reading for any reason (including uncorrected vision impairment)You have a phone, and a laptop with a webcam.

column1: First, you will complete an online intake questionnaire which asks you about your basic demographic data. Then, before the Testing session, we will ask about your attitudes regarding COVID-19 and your attitude towards government restrictions to limit the spread of COVID-19. The online questionnaire should take you less than 10 minutes. During the testing phase, you will be asked to interact with the chatbot for 30 minutes on your smartphone while being supervised by an experimenter via Zoom. In these 30 minutes, you will be asked to converse with the chatbot in order to get answers to specific questions in sequence. Afterwards, you will be asked to freely interact with Cory Covid-Bot for 30 minutes (without any supervision). Lastly, you will be asked to complete an exit survey (also online) wherein you provide feedback on your experience with Cory Covid-Bot and general questions about your attitudes on COVID-19 after accessing information on the subject.
Consenting to participate in the research

Participation in this research is completely voluntary. It is your decision to participate or not. If you choose to participate, you will be asked to sign a consent form, and you can take a screenshot of this form to keep, or request one after the questionnaire from one of the researchers.

You may withdraw from the research at any stage. If you would like to also withdraw any of your data which has not yet been published, you can contact any of the researchers listed at the top of this Explanatory Statement and they will remove your data from the study with no repercussions to you.

The research team may discontinue your participating in the study at any point, for scientific reasons. If discontinued, you can request that your data be removed from the study with no repercussions to you.

To cover costs associated with your time, you will receive a $50 Coles Voucher for participating fully in the study. This will be sent to you via email within 24hrs after completion of the whole experiment (including post-test survey).

Any information obtained in connection with this research project that can identify you will remain confidential. It will only be disclosed with your permission, except as required by law. The data obtained in this study will be only accessible by the research team listed above. Publicly presented or published data will only include numerical data and statistical analyses. It will not include any information which may identify you.

In accordance with Monash University regulations, if you decide to take part in this study, you will be assigned a number and all hard copy and electronic files containing data from you will be labelled with this number, rather than your name or other information, which could directly identify you. A document detailing which number corresponds with you, and any other details that could identify you, will be kept on a password-protected network at Monash University accessible only to researchers directly involved in this study. This document will be deleted at the conclusion of this study to protect your confidentiality. We will keep your data for 5 years and then destroy it by shredding (for hard copy files) or deletion (for electronic files).
This study is funded by the Department of Human and Health Services.
If you would like to be informed of the aggregate findings of this research project, please contact the researchers via email.
Should you have any concerns or complaints about the conduct of the project, you are welcome to contact the Executive Officer, Monash University Human Research Ethics (MUHREC):
